      "title": "Lonoke’s Morris to take superintendent’s job in Yell County",
      "text": "11:43 am - April 20, 2016 Lonoke’s Morris to take superintendent’s job in Yell County Nathan Morris \nBy Donna Lampkin Stephens \nNathan Morris, Lonoke’s girls basketball coach and athletic director as well as the district’s director of support services, is leaving after 11 years to become the superintendent of the Two Rivers School District in Yell County. \nMorris, 40, compiled an overall record of 230-113, including the last 11 seasons atop the Lady Jackrabbit program, and spent the last four as AD. He will begin his new job July 1. \n“I love the job I’m leaving, and because of that, it was going to take the right job to get me to leave,” he said. “I don’t feel like I’ve worked a day in 11 years. I loved every day of it, and even the days some would consider to be challenging or bad days, they were still good to me. \n“That’s just a tribute to the people here, the school, the students and former students and, most especially, my former players and current players. They made this the best stop I could imagine.” \nMorris finished his superintendent’s certificate last spring through Texas A&M-Texarkana. \n“I knew when I first got into coaching that I wasn’t sure if I’d be in it 30, 35 years because at some point a principal or superintendent’s job would interest me,” he said. “The last couple of years I’ve been afforded the opportunity to be in a central office role in Lonoke, and going to school and getting that certificate has put me in that direction to start looking.” \nThe support services sector of his job has included transportation, maintenance, food service and custodial services for the district. \n“Two Rivers was just a good fit. It certainly wasn’t something that I felt like I had to go. But it was just the right timing. The timing is key. It’s a great opportunity, and I didn’t know if the same one would come along in the next couple of years, so I felt like it was best to get on it now.” \nHe said Two Rivers was the first superintendent’s position he had pursued. \n“I wasn’t going to a place where I didn’t want to be,” he said. “We were looking for a good fit.” \nTwo Rivers in Yell County is the consolidated district of students from Ola, Plainview-Rover, Fourche Valley and Casa. \nMorris grew up in Beebe, and earned a Master of Arts in Teaching from the University of Arkansas in 1999 before taking his first coaching job at Dardanelle, where he spent four years with duties including assistant boys basketball and head baseball and softball. He then went to Camden Fairview for two years as assistant boys basketball coach and head softball and junior boys basketball coach before coming to Lonoke as head girls basketball coach. He added AD duties four years ago. Along the way, he finished a program of study in educational leadership for his principal’s license from Harding University in 2010. \nHe said Sunday applications for the girls basketball job were being sought for another week. \n“AD and my other duties are still kind of up in the air,” he said. “For the coaching job, I’ll compile a list and get it in the hands of the people it needs to go to. There will probably be a committee formed. \n“But I’m still here and running the athletic department until I’m done and a replacement is made. We’re going on, business as usual.” \nHe said he hoped those choices would be made by the May board meeting, scheduled for May 16, so the new coach would be able to start by early June for the Lady Jackrabbits’ summer schedule. \n“It is bittersweet because it’s been good,” he said of leaving Lonoke. “I’ve got probably enough coaching memories here in 11 years to last people 10 lifetimes. The kids here have been great. I’ve picked up more from them than they got from me.” \nHe said he had talked to multiple coaches about how to now when it’s time to make such a career change. \n“Everybody says you know, but you also know there’s probably no going back (to coaching),” he said. “But who knows? I could show back up as a seventh grade coach or a junior high basketball coach or a softball coach. It’s in my blood, and I don’t think it could ever leave. \n“Certainly next November, when the balls start bouncing, it’ll be a little disappointing, probably whole lot of me that wants to be out there. But these are new challenges, and instead of trying to win one on the floor or through the entire athletic department, I’m going to try to put my energy into winning with the whole school district. I’m looking forward to it. It’s a challenge and that’s what life’s about — accepting challenges and taking them on full-speed.” \nAbout to finish his 17th year in education, he could retire in 11 years. \n“I could easily see myself doing this until then,” he said. “You never know where the road leads, but I know the road through Lonoke’s been pretty good to me.”",
