      "text": "Share this URL Kathy Kmonicek/Kathy Kmonicek Marcella Sills argues in court papers filed in Manhattan Supreme Court that the labor contract covering principals “specifies no particular start time.” \nA grade school principal in Far Rockaway who was fired in February for repeatedly being late and absent has sued to get her $128,000 a year job back. \nMarcella Sills, who was the principal of P.S. 106 from 2005 to 2014 when she was reassigned, argues in court papers filed Wednesday in Manhattan Supreme Court that the labor contract covering principals “specifies no particular start time.” \n“Accordingly, without a start time, there can’t be a late time,” her lawyer Douglas Rosenthal argues. \nQUEENS HIGH SCHOOL PRINCIPAL ACCUSED OF SEXUAL HARASSMENT, INFLATING GRADES IN TWO FEDERAL LAWSUITS \nAn arbitrator ruled earlier this year that because Sills’ expected reporting time was 8:30 a.m. when students arrive, she should be fired because she failed to be there on numerous occasions. \nThe arbitrator said Sills’ contract argument “defies common sense” because the contract has never been applied that way. \nRosenthal says the arbitrator exceeded his authority because school officials have stated that principals must work 7 hours and 15 minutes a day — but have not specified which hours. \nPS 106, which was clobbered by the Sandy, made headlines in 2014 when it was revealed that Sills had no Common Core textbooks, no art and no gym for students who often spent their days watching movies. \nA Law Department spokesman said “it’s entirely proper to fire a principal who persistently fails to show up for work on time. We'll review the complaint and respond accordingly.” Related Stories",
