      "title": "Employers seek veterans&apos; skill set at Great Lakes job fair",
      "text": "As an aviation structure mechanic, Kraig Reed used to restore the bodywork of aircraft when he was in the Navy.\nWhile serving the country, Reed got to travel to Singapore, Australia, Hong Kong and Diego Garcia, an island located south of the equator in the central Indian Ocean, where Reed said he often saw hundreds of sharks while he worked.\n\"It's a breeding ground for many marine animals, and it's really something to see,\" Reed said.\nOn Thursday, the 57-year-old Milwaukee resident was looking for something a little different to do with his time while visiting the biannual veteran's job fair at Great Lakes.\nDuring the event, 200 hundred military members and their families visited 80 booths where employers and veterans-organization officials eagerly greeted them and invited them to learn more about their agencies.\nSharon Huiett, chief operating officer of the Glenview-based software sales company LDG/Team Lear, said she was happy to participate in the fair.\n\"I'm looking for people who are hungry to work and have the gift of gab,\" Huiett said. \"Those highly motivated and energetic folks.\"\nOn Thursday, Huiett found two candidates who fit that description, and they'll likely be getting a call with a job offer, she said.\nWaukegan District 60 considers expanding student laptop program Emily K. Coleman The one-to-one technology initiative that put a device in the hands of every Waukegan High School student could be spreading to middle school, officials said.\nThe Waukegan School District 60 Board of Education is set to make the call at its Tuesday board meeting on whether the expansion will occur.\n... The one-to-one technology initiative that put a device in the hands of every Waukegan High School student could be spreading to middle school, officials said.\nThe Waukegan School District 60 Board of Education is set to make the call at its Tuesday board meeting on whether the expansion will occur.\n... (Emily K. Coleman) Ted Uchiek, deputy chief in the corrections department of the Lake County Sheriff's Office, said he believes veterans often make great law enforcement employees. \"But I might be a little biased,\" Uchiek joked, as he served 22 years in the Navy and retired as a senior chief in 1998.\n\"People who have been in the service know how to follow orders and the chain of command,\" Uchiek said. \"Not many think of the jail when they're looking for job opportunities, but there are plenty.\"\nCorrections officers and deputy sheriffs were on hand to discuss the work with those who were interested.\nAt the American Legion booth, Wayne T. Macejak, director at the Veterans Affairs and Rehabilitation department, answered questions about veteran benefits available to them and their family members.\n\"Have you heard of the GI Bill?\" Macejak asked those who walked by. \"The American Legion drafted it,\" he said before they had a chance to answer him. Then he handed them a pamphlet with information on many more benefits created by the federal program..\nFrom banks to delivery companies and coffee houses, the veterans' job fair provided a host of opportunities for those looking to slow down the pace and get ready to retire to start a career outside the military.\n\"People who attend these fairs come from all walks of life and from all over the world, and we think that's very attractive to employers,\" said Kevin Jones of the Great Lakes Family Employment Readiness Program.\nWhile Reed's job search would go beyond Thursday, he's participating in the Vocational Rehabilitation Unit at Great Lakes, where veterans train to develop skills for jobs outside the service. Reed is looking for employment in the medical field, such as a medical supplies technician, which is a job he's performed.\nThe veterans' job fair is sponsored twice a year by Naval Station Great Lakes Fleet and Family Support Center Transition Assistance Program and Family Employment Readiness Program, and the Captain James A. Lovell Federal Health Care Center Vocational Rehabilitation Program.\n ",
