      "title": "Students attending job fair prepare for future",
      "text": "Close Staff photo by Cathy Spaulding \nIndian Capital Technology Center student Yesenia Ochoa shows the resume she had ready Friday for the ICTC career fair. featured Students attending job fair prepare for future By Cathy Spaulding Phoenix Staff Writer 5 hrs ago Staff photo by Cathy Spaulding \nIndian Capital Technology Center student Yesenia Ochoa shows the resume she had ready Friday for the ICTC career fair. \nIndian Capital Technology Center students came prepared to work Friday — and dozens of prospective employers were ready to talk to them. \nICTC's annual job fair brought students and employers together Friday at its Muskogee campus. \n\"It's a full house today,\" said ICTC public information coordinator Anesa Hooper. \"We have 70 vendors.\" \nStudents in ICTC's high school and adult programs filled the campus conference center. \n\"A lot have resumes in hand,\" Hooper said. \nICTC health care student, Yesenia Ochoa, a Muskogee High School junior, had several resumes in her binder. She said she and classmate Gracie Perez were looking for jobs as certified nursing assistants and visited several booths. \n\"We liked all of them,\" Ochoa said, adding that she is interested in getting a summer job to help her save for college. \nOchoa is seeking a career as a pediatric surgeon. Perez said she plans to be a registered nurse. \nJustin Coats and Josh Cole, classmates in ICTC's auto mechanics, wore coats and ties as they walked along aisles of vendors. \n\"You've got to look good if you want a good job, someone to hire you,\" said Coats, a Fort Gibson High School senior. \nCole, a Porter High School senior, said he talked with several vendors and was interested in the National Guard. \nVendors included representatives of the armed forces, colleges, health care providers, businesses and manufacturers. \n\"We wanted to get out and meet students and let them know we want to open our door to students and future employees,\" said Darrin Smith, vice president of human resources and safety for Griffin Foods. \nSmith said Griffin offers opportunities for internships in food safety, as well as part time employment. \nMuskogee's Gospel Rescue Mission even had a booth. \n\"We are hoping youth will come join us as volunteers or staffing to help the community,\" said Executive Director Rich Schaus. He said the mission is seeking a staff member to help encourage clients. \nICTC Superintendent Tony Pivec said Friday's career fair was \"one of our best turnouts ever.\" \n\"One of the students was telling a teacher he had to go back to the classroom to print out more resumes,\" Pivec said. \nHe praised ICTC job placement specialist D'Amber D. Desmuke Bunch for setting up the fair. \n\"She focused on employers that matched programs we have,\" he said. \nA career fair is set for May 6 at ICTC's Tahlequah campus. \nReach Cathy Spaulding at (918) 684-2928 or . Sign Up / Sign In With your existing account from... {* loginWidget *}",
