      "title": "Students tour Barren County industries, learn about local jobs",
      "text": "Public Notices Statewide Close Glasgow High Schools students tour Amneal Pharmaceuticals on Wednesday as Mike Smith, the human resource director for Glasgow, talks to them about what job opportunities are available. Seniors from Glasgow, Caverna and Glasgow Christian Academy toured Wednesday. Barren County seniors toured Thursday. \nJames Brown / Glasgow Daily Times editor's pick featured Students tour Barren County industries, learn about local jobs By JAMES BROWN jbrown@glasgowdailytimes.com 19 hrs ago Glasgow High Schools students tour Amneal Pharmaceuticals on Wednesday as Mike Smith, the human resource director for Glasgow, talks to them about what job opportunities are available. Seniors from Glasgow, Caverna and Glasgow Christian Academy toured Wednesday. Barren County seniors toured Thursday. \nJames Brown / Glasgow Daily Times \nLevi Shaw learned his preconception of local industrial facilities is not reality. \n“The factories were a lot cleaner than I thought they were,” the Glasgow Christian Academy senior said Wednesday. \nShaw was among 178 seniors from GCA, Glasgow High School and Caverna High School who toured industry facilities and T.J. Samson Community Hospital in Barren County on Wednesday. Another 275 seniors from Barren County High School did the tours Thursday. \nShaw was among two waves of students who visited Akebono Brake’s facility on Cleveland Avenue and Amneal Pharmaceuticals on Beaver Trail. The first wave Wednesday at Amneal was comprised of Glasgow seniors. They heard stories from employees about what it takes to make it in today’s manufacturing workforce and what hiring professionals want in employees. \nThe pharmaceutical facility is primarily a distribution center, but within there are sales team positions, internet technology jobs and even corporate-level supply chain jobs where the employee is based in Glasgow. \nMatt Beals was the latter. \n“I started with Amneal working summers while in school,” Beals told the more than 20 Glasgow students gathered in the employee break room at the facility. “I enjoyed it. I had the attitude that I was going to work hard. I didn’t want people to think that just because it was a summer job that I wasn’t going to work hard.” \nHe graduated from the University of Kentucky with a degree in secondary education social studies, but decided that field was not for him and he returned to Amneal with a full-time position in drug supply chain security. \nDakota Walden came to work at Amneal not long after graduating high school and has moved up from a warehouse floor employee to a warehouse supervisor in two years. \n“I want the best for myself. You don’t get to that point by hanging back,” Walden said. “You’ve got to be the person who says, ‘I’ll do that.’” \nWalden said he planned to be a machinist, but has found what he considers to be a better path for himself. \n“I thought I was going to work in a machine shop the rest of my life,” he said. \nMike Smith, the Amneal human resources representative in Glasgow, told the students work ethic, appearance and self-motivation are key to being hired for a job and being successful once a person is employed. \n“I want someone who can carry themselves,” he said. \nMorgan Atwell, 20, is someone who can carry herself, Smith said. \nAtwell wanted a position in the warehouse and has impressed her supervisors with her work ethic and desire to do the job well. \n“I was brought up to work hard. When you work hard for a company, they will recognize it,” she said. “It follows you and they remember that.” \nOn Thursday, Regan Taylor and some of her Barren County senior classmates toured Akebono Brake and were impressed by what they saw in the facility and the impact it has beyond the boundaries of their home county. \n“I did not know that it shipped all over the world and that Glasgow, Kentucky impacted the world so much,” she said. \n“I really liked the part about how they make the calipers for the vehicles,” Nichole Wilcher said. “I really liked that part because it makes me think of how I can work on my own trucks on my own and maybe get a job here after I graduate high school. \n“ I really liked it. It made me think of how I need to get a job after I graduate and make my own money to support myself, and not only myself, but whoever I wind up with.” \nThe industry tours are part of a combined effort of Industrial Development Economic Authority of Glasgow-Barren County, Western Kentucky University-Glasgow and Southcentral Kentucky Community and Technical College and others to expand workforce development in Barren County. \nBarren County Judge-Executive Micheal Hale has also been involved in the development of workforce through his roles at the state, regional and local level of workforce development boards. \nHe provided surveys to the students Wednesday for their feedback on how effective the tours had been at informing them about employment opportunities in the community. \n“We want your input on how today was for you and so that we can make it better for next year,” Hale said during a debrief in the Glasgow High School auditorium. \nShaw said prior to receiving the survey that he has no plans of applying for any of the industry jobs, but, “I know of people that it would be good for them, especially (the opportunity) for different careers.” Sign Up / Sign In With your existing account from... {* loginWidget *}",
