        "title": "Clark students speak out about undocumented status, DACA policy \nMA_Worcester_Telegram WORCESTER – Rodrigo Saavedra and Nathanael S. Aragon Cooper have come a long way from the situations their families left two decades ago. But as they’re frequently reminded by their country’s government – and some of the people who seek to run it – they haven’t come far enough.\nMr. Saavedra and Mr. Aragon Cooper, both 22 and seniors at Clark University, have been living in the U.S. undocumented since they were brought here 18 and 20 years ago, respectively. The controversial program that’s given them hope for their futures in America, meanwhile – the Deferred Action for Childhood Arrivals, or DACA, policy – hangs in the balance, as the Supreme Court weighs a state’s challenge to a proposed expansion of the policy.\nInitially proposed by President Barack Obama four years ago as an executive order, DACA is intended to address, albeit temporarily, the plights of undocumented immigrants such as Mr. Saavedra and Mr. Aragon Cooper who were too young at the time to have any real say in their immigration to the U.S. The program grants undocumented residents who entered the country before their 16th birthday and before June 2007 a renewable two-year work permit, and spares them from deportation.\nIn 2012, Mr. Obama announced an expansion to the original policy that would have changed the cutoff for the year of arrival to 2010 and eliminated the existing age requirement. He also proposed DACA’s sister policy, the Deferred Action for Parents of Americans program, which extends DACA’s protections to undocumented immigrant parents of U.S. citizens or otherwise legal residents.\nBut Texas and other states subsequently sued to prevent both programs from going forward, leading to a federal court injunction that has temporarily halted their implementation, and landed the case before the Supreme Court. The eight-justice panel held oral arguments on Monday and is expected to deliver a decision either next month or in June.\nEva Millona, executive director of the Massachusetts Immigrant and Refugee Advocacy Coalition, was one of thousands of immigration advocates who took part in a rally in Washington, D.C., on Monday outside of the Supreme Court.\n“It was quite powerful, to listen to the families, to listen to their stories, and to hear their eagerness,” she said. “Really their only chance is to win this case.”\nWhile it’s not the permanent, legislative immigration reform the group has long been hoping for, MIRA is “extremely supportive of the president’s orders,” Ms. Millona added. “It at least provides a legal path for people (to stay in the country), even if it’s temporary.\n“We know it’s a Band-Aid solution, and it’s not what we really want. But this is the first step in fixing part of (the immigration system).”\nOn the other end of the political spectrum, however, opponents of DACA and DAPA have decried what they see as Mr. Obama’s overstepping the laws of the land, and single-handedly ruling on an issue that should be left to Congress.\n“I think even people who support the president’s objectives should be concerned about the precedent this could set,” said Ira Mehlman, a representative of the Federation for American Immigration Reform.\nIn addition, from a policy standpoint, Mr. Obama’s orders “essentially remove any meaningful restriction on immigration to the United States,” he said. “It undermines the (nation’s) whole immigration policy.”\nFor DACA specifically, the losers would appear to be millennial Americans, Mr. Mehlman argues, who are now suddenly faced with even more competition from undocumented immigrants in an already meager job market for new graduates.\nMr. Saavedra and Mr. Aragon Cooper have heard those arguments, as well as the rhetoric from presidential candidates like Republican Donald Trump, who infamously branded illegal immigrants as rapists in a speech last year. But like many beneficiaries of DACA, they’re not sure where else they’re supposed to go.\n“I feel American in every way, except in the way the American government defines,” said Mr. Aragon Cooper, whose mother fled with him from Mexico and a dangerous domestic situation. “I feel like people shouldn’t listen to the rhetoric, and get to know the people in their communities.”\nFor both him and Mr. Saavedra, the realities of their situations as undocumented residents set in during their junior year of high school, a time when the rest of their classmates were “getting jobs, getting driver’s permits – you realized you couldn’t have those things,” Mr. Aragon Cooper said.\nBattling depression, he said “it was grinding just to have to go to school. In the back of your head, you thought, ‘This might just be a waste of time.’ ”\nBoth he and Mr. Saavedra, whose family fled their native Peru, ultimately credit their networks of support – friends and family, as well as immigration activists – with helping them overcome their status and go to college. DACA, meanwhile, has given them a chance to work, as well. Mr. Saavedra, for instance, has been able to work at a legal firm in Boston under the program.\n“It’s opened up opportunities I otherwise would not have had,” said Mr. Aragon Cooper, who hopes to enroll in medical school after graduation, although his status will continue to hinder his chances to receive financial aid.\nTheir situations are not rare in the region, according to Clark University political science professor Heather Silber Mohamed, who cited recent Migration Policy Institute data estimating around 13,000 undocumented immigrants in the Worcester area would be affected by DACA and DAPA. She also said most citizens are largely in favor of those immigrants staying in the U.S., according to recent polling.\n“What we’ve seen really consistently over time is a majority of Americans support a path to citizenship,” she said, adding there has also been a corresponding drop in the number of people who believe all illegal immigrants should be deported.\n“I think the issue of immigration is cyclical – it’s come up throughout history,” Mr. Saavedra said. “Changes (to America’s immigration system) may be slow and piecemeal, but I’m very hopeful we’ll see immigration reform happen.”\nYoung undocumented people like Mr. Saavedra and Mr. Aragon Cooper are playing an increasingly important role in that process, according to Ms. Millona, who credited them for being “very vocal, in terms of their advocacy … they have brought their human stories to the picture.”\nMr. Saavedra, who said he is involved in immigration activism, pointed out DACA has given him a relative safe position from which to speak out. But he was also talking about being an undocumented resident when he was in high school, before Mr. Obama’s order was in effect.\n“In the media, (our message) gets muddled, misinterpreted, or straight up ignored at times,” he said. “And (speaking out) might put me at risk. But it also might help others.”\nScott O’Connell can be reached at Scott.O’Connell@telegram.com. Follow him on Twitter @ScottOConnellTG",
