      "title": "Full-time job is no guarantee of a home",
      "text": "April 22, 2016 12:47 AM CDT April 22, 2016 01:32 AM CDT Full-time job is no guarantee of a home Full-time job is no guarantee of a home Staff Writer Published: 22 April 2016 12:47 AM \nA quarter of the people who say they’re homeless are holding down full-time jobs, according to a recent study conducted by the Denton County Homeless Coalition. \nOn Thursday, Giving Hope Inc. officials presented the findings of the Point-in-Time count, an annual survey of the county’s homeless population, during a State of the Homeless for Denton County seminar. Giving Hope, a nonprofit, advocates for and assists people who are homeless or at risk of becoming homeless. \nOn Jan. 21, about 50 volunteers helped conduct the survey, which estimates the number of homeless and assesses their needs. The survey identified nearly 230 people who are homeless in Denton. \nOf those, 25.7 percent said they hold down full-time jobs. Yet they’re still unable to draw enough income for an application fee, deposit and upfront rent to move into an apartment, officials say. \n“That’s always a shock … the people who [are] homeless, they have a full-time job, but it’s just not enough to get them three times the rent they need to get into an apartment,” said Alonzo Peterson, executive director of Giving Hope. “People just assume that they’re homeless and not working.” \nIt’s even more difficult for those with a criminal record to find a landlord who will rent to them, he said. \nAbout 70 percent of the people surveyed said they are able to work. Nearly 53 percent were unemployed and looking for work. But, Peterson said, it’s extremely difficult to find work when you have to haul all your belongings to a job interview, or don’t have reliable access to a phone or email to follow up with employers. \nThe survey indicates that six months is the median length of unemployment. \nSince the last Point-in-Time survey, the numbers have remained relatively the same. In 2015, the survey found 234 people in Denton who identified themselves as homeless. \nThe Texas Homeless Network, an Austin-based organization that offers solutions for ending homelessness in the state, uses a formula to determine the annual estimated homeless and transient population living in each county. In 2014, the organization reported an estimated 1,600 homeless and transient people lived in Denton County. The 2016 estimate was unavailable Thursday night. \nMore and more people are homeless longer now than in previous years, Peterson said. \nThe largest contributing factors to homelessness locally include substance abuse, financial reasons, unemployment and health issues, according to the survey. \nPoint-in-Time counts are taken around the country over a 24-hour period in January. Volunteers visit areas where homeless people congregate, focusing on shelters because that’s where most people are expected to be during cold weather. \nThe counts offers a snapshot of the homeless population on the day the survey was taken. The data is analyzed and used for planning purposes to tackle homelessness. The U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development requires the Point-in-Time count for counties that receive federal funding. \nPeterson said the local data will soon be analyzed and compared with data from 2015. \nOn Thursday, city and school officials, hospital representatives and church ministry leaders attended the State of the Homeless seminar, which lasted more than two hours. \nA separate presentation, given by Christy Daniel, a social worker with youth advocacy group Journey to Dream, shed light on the number of homeless youths in Denton County. \nMore than 2,000 children in Denton County were reported homeless during the 2014-15 school year, Daniel told seminar attendees. About 400 of the children were high school students. \nAbout 70 percent were living in hotels, staying in cars or sleeping on someone’s couch, while the other 30 percent were on the streets, she said. \nShe said 46 percent of the youths left home because of abusive situations, and 40 percent were kicked out or abandoned because of their sexual identity. \nDaniel said nearly 1 in 7 youths between ages 10 and 18 run away at least once, and of those, 70 percent leave home spontaneously with no plan. \nJourney to Dream intends to open Kyle’s Place, a shelter for unaccompanied homeless youths, this September in Lewisville, she said. \nCourtney Cross, United Way of Denton County’s community impact coordinator for homelessness initiatives, discussed the Denton County Homelessness Leadership Team during Thursday’s seminar. \nThe oversight committee of 15 to 20 members will begin meeting next month and will be tasked with looking at ways to address homelessness and housing services. The effort is funded by the United Way and the city of Denton. \n\nBRITNEY TABOR can be reached at 940-566-6876 and via Twitter at @BritneyTabor. \nBRITNEY TABOR can be reached at 940-566-6876 and via Twitter at @BritneyTabor.",
