      "title": "",
      "text": "This is a classic example of why the media is out of touch. The jobs described in this article are not \"middle class,\" they are, if anything, \"working class.\" Yes, repititious jobs are disappearing because they can be done more efficiently by machines and computers but there are thousands of jobs that don't require a college degree but employers are using a degree as a weeding out factor. I worked for almost 40 years in the aviation industry, including about half that time for two major corporations as a corporate pilot. I spent 12 years in the military and did not have a college degree, nor did most of my fellow pilots. Now, its almost impossible for a young pilot to get a job without a degree, not because a degree makes anyone a better pilot, but because there are a lot of pilots with degrees of some sort and HR people (who are degreed) have been conditioned to give degrees more weight than they should. Of course, that's because that's what they were taught in college. The real problem is academia - they have created degrees for professions and skills that really don't require a degree. (BTW, two of my children have masters degrees, including one from Harvard, but that doesn't make them any more suited for most jobs than if they didn't have one.) This all started in the 60s when Congress started providing student loans and grants and colleges saw an opportunity to bring in more revenue so they came up with new degrees.",
