      "title": "Director: Jobs there; but few qualified",
      "text": "Director: Jobs there; but few qualified FIX: Budget cuts, lack of transporatation among barriers to connecting workers with employment By DENISE A. RAYMO Press-Republican 3 hrs ago \nMALONE — Jobs are available in Franklin County, but other issues exist beyond employment skills that people lack. \nSylvie Nelson of the North Country Workforce Development Board recently told legislators it’s especially difficult to connect with potential workers ages 16 to 24 and get them the training and job-skill services they need to be more employable. \nBut there is more to it. \n“It’s nice that you want everybody to have jobs, but when you don’t take care of the problems at the source — when you have people who have no transportation, no day-care service or they’re in abusive relationships or have substance-abuse problems — you can’t expect them to be great employees because they have other issues that are bigger,” she said. \n“But by working together to solve these problems, then we can put them in (the available) jobs, and they would be in a better mental state to be more employable. That whole progression is lacking.” \n\nBUDGET SHIFT \nEarlier in her presentation, Nelson said her board represents Clinton, Franklin, Essex and Hamilton counties and that regional strategic planning for employment had not been done for years. \nMembers recently developed a plan that re-energized the board and gave it a fresh direction and progressive goals to pursue on behalf of the underemployed and unemployed. \nShe said 75 percent of the agency’s budget used to go to reach in-school students and 25 percent for those out of school. \nBut that division of effort has recently been reversed so 75 percent of the funding goes to those out of school who are either not trying to break into the workforce or are having a hard time doing so because they lack certain skills or training. \nThe agency offers literacy services for people who need to sharpen or expand their writing and communication skills, job-search or unemployment help, assistance for those with disabilities or special needs and services targeting youths. \nOneWorkSource sites offer a variety of job-assistance services for business owners and potential employees. \n\nTRANSPORTATION LACKING \nJob seekers submit a resume through the State Department of Labor, which is circulated throughout the region and seen by potential employers with job needs. \nAt the same time, the office makes sure applicants are notified of new job postings that meet their qualifications. \n“It’s like an employment service, but it’s done by the state,” Nelson said. \nEliminating social barriers and having too few people qualified for some jobs are where efforts must be concentrated, she said. \nMany potential employees have no vehicle or other means to get to work, but some who live in Franklin County are relying on that county’s Public Transportation Service to get to jobs in Clinton County. \n“It’s filling a need in the Plattsburgh area, so there is a lot of cooperation,” she said. \n\nHUGE GAP \nBut even as the Development Board is trying to help the local economy by filling vacant jobs, Nelson said, the state slashed her budget by 15 percent. \n“We’re going to have to serve less people,” she said, “and we still have a huge gap. We have more jobs than people to fill them.” \nLegislators Chairman Billy Jones (D-Chateaugay) said the tough part is matching the positions and people. \n“There are jobs out there,\" he said. \"We just have to find the right fit and get people into those jobs.\"",
