      "title": "Young voters prioritizing jobs, economy in election",
      "text": "Vote Campaign \nThe upcoming Pennsylvania primary marks the first voting opportunity for many millennial voters. \nThe November primary will be the first national-scale election in which Generation Y voters make up the same amount, if not more, of the eligible electorate than the baby-boomers. This makes millennial voters the largest generation in U.S. history. \nAccording to a 2015 census, those falling into the millennial generation, between the ages of 18 and 30, account for 83.1 million versus 76.4 million in the baby boomers generation. And while these are general numbers that don't specify participating voters, experts are not counting these young votes as insignificant. \nFormer House Speaker Newt Gingrich urged a crowd of young voters in Houston in March, \"This is really important because this is the first election that millennials have the potential to be the largest voting bloc, more than seniors.\" \nThough the millennial voters are massive in numbers, their actual participation is unpromising. Some national politicians have donned these voters as the \"all throat, no vote\" generation. \nRecent changes to voter registration and poll-day protocols have made it less appealing, even inconvenient, for young voters to mark their ballots. Stricter voter identification requirements and polling hours that fail to align with college classes have made many millennials turn away from the process. What's more, those registering as independents or with some unspecified parties cannot vote in Pennsylvania's closed primary. \nAccording to information provided by Ed Allison, director of Voter Registration in Lawrence County, these non-affiliated millennials are a major concern. As of April 6, 1,202 combined voters born between 1986 and 1998 have registered in the county as Independent, No Affiliation, No Party, or Other. \nThat is compared to 3,179 registered Democrats and 2,951 registered Republicans on the same generation. Of Lawrence County voters in the same pool who voted in the last presidential election and are still registered with the same parties, there were 698 Democrats and 636 Republicans and 179 not affiliated with any particular party. Comparing these numbers to now, this would mean that there are 5,876 total assumed “new” millennial voters registered to vote this time around. \nAccording to Anne Walther, a sophomore at Westminster College and head of the school's Young Republican efforts, uninformed, unaffiliated voters are detrimental to themselves. \n\"We want to inform people about what's going on,\" she said. \"A lot of students don't know the difference between a Republican and a Democrat. We're trying to help inform people.\" \nWalther hopes that by holding issue-specific discussion groups and voter-registration events, her campus group can make a difference in voting numbers on election day. \n\"The most dangerous thing besides a non-voter is a misinformed voter,\" she said. \n\"Foreign policy really scares me. The economy ... we have a system where people are afraid of succeeding. The government needs to be a trampoline, not a safety net,\" Walther said. Of the issues most concerning to her, Walther said feeling secure after graduation is on the top of her list. \n\"We need a president who's going to create jobs and incentive for people to want to succeed. People can't rely on the government to bounce back,\" she said. \nWalther also expressed that while she doesn't necessarily agree with all of Donald Trump's campaign rhetoric, she believes he is the strongest candidate to oppose either Hillary Clinton or Bernie Sanders. \n\"Cruz just doesn't seem strong,\" she said. \"We need a republican and can't afford to divide the party. If we go to a contested convention, people will be very upset.\" \nElizabeth Stelle, a former executive for the former Lawrence County Young Republicans, which is no longer active in a formal capacity, agrees that keeping the GOP united is critical. \n\"People feel very strongly,\" she said, \"and I think that whatever happen, people realize how important growing the (Republican) party is. We need to unite for a cause and make change.\" \nStelle echoed Walther's sentiments of financial opportunity, saying she believes her generation is most concerned with economic growth. \n\"I'd say my generation is most concerned with not being able to get ahead. People my age still living with their parents...there's a lack of growth and it goes beyond party lines.\" \nAfter only becoming involved in politics after moving to Lawrence County five years ago, Stelle said she has seen her peers in their 20's and 30's \"disgusted\" with the lack of bipartisan effort in Washington. Though she doesn't side with any particular candidate entirely, she believes that pushing local issues is the first step in seeing changes happen on the national level. \n\"It's important to take action in what's going on, inform yourself, because what happens in Lawrence County effects you more in your every day life,\" Stelle said. \n(Email: )",
