      "title": "Vandermolen takes GVSU job",
      "text": "BY MATT TROUTMAN mtroutman@record-eagle.com 3 hrs ago \nTRAVERSE CITY — A principal slated for the top job at Courtade Elementary School will instead leave K-12 education altogether. \nTraverse City Central High School Principal Rick Vandermolen said Tuesday he has accepted a full-time teaching position at Grand Valley State University. He said he'll resign from a 14-year career with Traverse City Area Public Schools effective June 30. \n\"There’s so many memories,\" he said. \"It’s been a wonderful part of my career.\" \nTCAPS officials in March announced that Vandermolen would transfer to Courtade Elementary School to serve as its principal. \nSuperintendent Paul Soma acknowledged being a little surprised when he learned that Vandermolen accepted the GVSU position, but said it made sense given that Vandermolen in the last couple years spoke about becoming a professor. \n\"What we have to do now is look at the void that’s created at Courtade,\" Soma said. \nWestwoods Elementary School Principal Jessie Houghton will take over Vandermolen's position at Central High School. \nVandermolen recently came under fire following the abrupt resignation of Central varsity girls basketball coach Heather Simpson. Complaints about a lack of administrative support for Simpson prompted TCAPS officials to launch an investigation. \nThat probe ended with Associate Superintendent Sander Scott filing a strongly-worded reprimand in Vandermolen's personnel file, which Vandermolen refuted and refused to sign. Vandermolen said the situation had nothing to do with his application for the GVSU job. \n\"No, it didn’t have any bearing on this position that I’ve applied for and accepted,\" he said. He applied for the job in late February or early March, he said. \nVandermolen said he'll teach classes for master's and education specialist degrees. He said he believes his experiences will help support the principals and aspiring principals he'll end up teaching. \nIt also creates the chance, however slight, that Soma could be one of his students. Soma is working toward his master's degree at GVSU and said he only has two classes left. He said Vandermolen — who will continue to live in the Traverse City area — will maintain personal and professional ties to TCAPS. \n\"If I had five or six classes to go, it wouldn’t surprise me if he was teaching one,\" Soma said. Sign Up / Sign In With your existing account from... {* loginWidget *}",
