      "title": "On-the-job training for Forestview students",
      "text": "On-the-job training for Forestview students Comment By Wade Tyler Millward wmillward@gastongazette.com Gaston Gazette By Wade Tyler Millward wmillward@gastongazette.com Posted Apr. 27, 2016 at 5:41 PM Updated at 5:41 PM By Wade Tyler Millward wmillward@gastongazette.com Posted Apr. 27, 2016 at 5:41 PM Two Forestview High School students have been put to work by one of the county’s largest employers. David Aviles and Alex Hillsman are working part time at American & Efird as part of a new program at the school. The teens applied, went through an interview process and even passed drug tests and background checks to work for the industrial textile company based in Mount Holly. Both teens are now helping technicians at a company plant. They leave Forestview every weekday after their third classes and work from around 2 p.m. to 6 p.m. This program is the first of its kind for the high school and for the company, said Heather Forbes, the school’s career development coordinator. She hopes the school can continue to offer students to work part time at American & Efird. In exchange, the company helps prepare students with technical skills that will get them jobs after graduation, Forbes said. “We’d love to expand the program and open it to more than just two students,” she said. “It depends on the needs of the company.” Aviles and Hillsman have are earning school credit from work to make up for missed classes. They were accepted into the program at Forestview thanks in part to teacher recommendation, Forbes said. Forestview’s career training program focuses on manufacturing and electrical trades. Other schools in the county offer other specialties like automotive, she said. She believes Aviles and Hillsman have been a good example of what Gaston schools can offer local employers. “They have done an excellent job,” she said. “They meshed well with A&E. We hear nothing but respect from all of their supervisors.\" By Wade Tyler Millward wmillward@gastongazette.com Gaston Gazette By Wade Tyler Millward wmillward@gastongazette.com Posted Apr. 27, 2016 at 5:41 PM",
