      "title": "Trump vows to stop job loss in Indianapolis campaign stop",
      "text": "Close Darron Cummings \nRepublican presidential candidate Donald Trump speaks during a campaign stop Wednesday, April 27, 2016, in Indianapolis. (AP Photo/Darron Cummings) Trump vows to stop job loss in Indianapolis campaign stop Former IU coach Bob Knight spoke in support of presidential hopeful By Christopher Stephens The Herald Bulletin 3 hrs ago Darron Cummings \nRepublican presidential candidate Donald Trump speaks during a campaign stop Wednesday, April 27, 2016, in Indianapolis. (AP Photo/Darron Cummings) \nINDIANAPOLIS — Presidential candidate Donald Trump's second rally in Indiana was markedly subdued as the candidate focused on preventing companies from leaving the United States and bad trade deals that he said had hurt Hoosier workers. \nWith the help of a Hoosier icon, former Indiana University basketball coach Bobby Knight, Trump got his message across. \nThe Indiana Farmer's Coliseum at the Indiana State Fairgrounds was packed with people holding red, white and blue signs supporting Trump on Wednesday night ahead of Tuesday's primary. \nThe event was calm compared to some Trump rallies, with protesters banned from the Fairgrounds. \nKnight introduced Trump at the rally, saying he can set the country on the right path. \n\"You will be responsible for the shift into what America should be if you vote for Donald Trump,\" Knight said to the crowd of several thousand strong. \nKevin Knight, an IU graduate student not related to Bobby Knight, attended the rally Wednesday and said he already planned to skip class and see Trump speak, but Bobby Knight's appearance \"sweetened the pot.\" \n\"He's an icon of Indiana history,\" Kevin Knight said. \"Having (Bobby) Knight here is an important way to connect with Hoosiers.\" \nJosh Anderson, South Bend, was wearing an IU sweatshirt at the rally and said Knight and Trump fit together because of their bombastic personalities. \n\"Just like Coach Knight, (Trump) speaks his mind, and I like them both for that,\" Anderson said. \nAfter Trump took the stage at the rally, he focused mainly on trade deals such as NAFTA and the Trans-Atlantic Partnership, which he said make it easier for American manufacturers to move overseas. He specifically called out Carrier, an HVAC manufacturing company that earlier this year announced that the business would move to Mexico, putting nearly 1,400 Hoosier workers out of jobs. \nSeveral former Carrier workers in the crowd called out to Trump, who said his plan to stop manufacturers from moving overseas was to charge a 35 percent tax on every product a company like Carrier ships into the United States. \n\"Then they will call and say, 'President, Carrier has decided to stay in Indiana,\" Trump said to thunderous applause and cheers of \"U-S-A!\" \nTrump's message to support American manufacturing jobs resonated with Mark Hale, who is still has not decided who to vote for Tuesday. Trump will be opposed by Ohio Gov. John Kasich and U.S. Sen. Ted Cruz of Texas. \nHale said he wanted to come out to see for himself what Trump was like. But Hale was already sold on Trump's message to \"make America great again,\" by keeping manufacturers from leaving. \nOne of Trump's sons, Donald Trump Jr., briefly took the stage alongside his father, saying America needs someone who has \"spent years signing the front of checks.\" \n\"Bring in someone who understands what job creation is,\" Trump Jr. urged. \"If you think the system is working, then fine. But I don't think a lot of people do. It's time for a change, and no one else is going to work harder for you.\" Sign Up / Sign In With your existing account from... {* loginWidget *}",
