      "title": "Business leaders say early childhood education funding is key to filling STEM jobs in future",
      "text": "Business leaders say early childhood education funding is key to filling STEM jobs in future Comment Posted Apr. 27, 2016 at 2:00 PM Updated at 5:58 PM Posted Apr 27, 2016 at 2:00 PM Updated at 5:58 PM Some Illinois business leaders said Wednesday the state needs to invest more in early childhood programs to ensure students will be prepared for future careers in fields requiring math and science education. Members of ReadyNation Illinois called on lawmakers to support a $75 million increase in early childhood programs that can help prevent children from falling behind early in academic areas that can prepare them to take jobs in fields related to science, technology, engineering and math, or STEM. Rudy Valdez, vice president of an economic development organization in Rockford, said the state is expected to add 100,000 jobs in the science and technology and health fields from 2010 to 2020, but some of those jobs will go unfilled because of a lack of qualified candidates. “Without focused efforts, we won’t be able to fill all of these positions with highly skilled, fully qualified workers,” he said. “We’re falling short. Research shows that high-quality early learning investments in young children can get us back on track.” Tom Fitch, vice president of Harold O’Shea Builders of Springfield, said more people are retiring from those positions than are entering them. “These are good-paying jobs,” he said. “Many of them boast salaries that are more than double the median U.S. salary. We have a continuing shortage of manpower, skilled labor, project managers that require good STEM skills. A better focus on early learning can help us lay a solid foundation for our future workforce.” Budget cuts have resulted in about 20,000 children losing access to state-funded preschool services. The group said Sangamon County lost 694 pre-K slots from 2009 to 2015, or nearly 36 percent. Gov. Bruce Rauner has called for an increase in early childhood programs and wants lawmakers to approve a K-12 education budget that will ensure schools open on time next fall. However, Senate President John Cullerton, D-Chicago, has indicated he first wants the state's school funding formula to be revised to ensure education dollars go to school districts that need them the most. Sean Noble, Illinois director of ReadyNation, said the group has not taken a position on the education funding formula proposal. — Contact Doug Finke: doug.finke @sj-r.com, 788-1527, twitter.com/dougfinkesjr . By",
