      "title": "Raimondo takes plans for education, job skills on tour",
      "text": "Raimondo takes plans for education, job skills on tour The governor hosts the first of a series of public discussions Thursday night in Cumberland. Comment Follow @@lborgprojocom Posted Apr. 28, 2016 @ 8:40 pm CUMBERLAND, R.I. — Governor Raimondo promoted her education agenda in Cumberland Thursday night, the first of a series of conversations in which the public will be invited to weigh in on her plans. After the discussion, Raimondo was asked if she needed to engage the public more in light of the negative response to her \"Cooler & Warmer\" tourism campaign. She said the fallout from that campaign was \"a reminder of the fact you have to engage people in everything,\" adding that she wants to be an accessible governor. Raimondo repeated what has become her education stump speech: that a high school diploma should mean something and that Rhode Island's economy depends on what skills are acquired by the next generation. She also outlined her major education proposals: a computer course in every school and making college more affordable by allowing high school students to gain college credits and boosting tuition aid. Raimondo stressed that her budget sets aside additional money for special education and English language learners. And she noted that it tries to level the playing field financially between traditional public schools and charter public schools. Her budget calls for giving school districts an additional $355 per student in state aid to cover costs not borne by charter schools. Districts with more than 5 percent enrollment in charters will receive an additional $300 per student. Although Cumberland officials have been vocal critics of charter schools, that sentiment wasn't widely evident Thursday night. Cumberland School Committee Chairwoman Lisa Beaulieu said that half of all new state education aid goes toward paying non-classroom-related expenditure, including charter school tuition, teacher pensions and transportation costs. Under the funding formula, the money follows the child from the district school to the charter. \"Charter schools will soon be our biggest unfunded mandate,\" she said. \"It's not an equitable situation.\" Raimondo acknowledged that the revised funding formula isn't perfect but said it's a step in the right direction. While charters do draw money away from the traditional school district, charters —and here she singled out Blackstone Valley Prep in northern Rhode Island — are doing \"terrific work.\" \"It's a balancing act,\" she said of the funding formula. On the role that standardized testing plays in education, Raimondo said that as a parent, she likes to know how her children are doing academically. But she also said, \"You can't over-test. I've been frustrated by that myself.\" Just this week, state Education Commissioner Ken Wagner proposed eliminating the Partnership for the Assessment of Readiness for College and Careers, the state's controversial new test, as a graduation requirement, although districts would be allowed to use it as a part of their graduation criteria. Wagner underscored that philosophy Thursday night, saying, \"We need a measure of student progress. However, tests must serve instruction and test preparation isn't good teaching.\" The lack of unstructured play time during the school day has become a hot topic in Rhode Island and nationwide. One Cumberland parent complained that her child is \"bouncing off the walls\" because he gets only 26 minutes a day for recess and lunch. Raimondo agreed but said she doesn't think the problem is best solved by passing legislation. Two bills seeking to mandate recess at the elementary level are before the General Assembly. \"Let's give schools more flexibility,\" Raimondo said. \"Don't regulate it.\" —lborg@providencejournal.com",
