      "title": "Raimondo reaches out after toughest month on job",
      "text": "Raimondo reaches out after toughest month on job 'Cooler & Warmer' debacle was followed by a poll that showed low approval numbers and Clinton's primary defeat Comment Follow @patrickanderso_ Posted Apr. 28, 2016 @ 9:24 pm CUMBERLAND, R.I. — Governor Raimondo can persuade a room, as she showed when making the case to overhaul the state pension system, cut the Medicaid budget and invest tens of millions of dollars in new economic development incentives. Now coming off perhaps her rockiest month since taking office, Raimondo is looking to reconnect with Rhode Islanders who may be skeptical of national magazine features and high-powered fundraisers or concerned she may have lost touch. On Thursday night, Raimondo traveled to Cumberland High School for a town-hall style discussion on education and work-force training, two subjects she has focused on all year, in the first stop of a statewide listening. \"Everything I have done in government, since I have been in government, whether it was pension reform or reinventing Medicaid ... the more you bring people with you, the more successful you will be,\" Raimondo told reporters after the event. \"So clearly with the mistakes with tourism, not bringing stakeholders to the table, was a reminder of that.\" The flubbed roll-out of the state's new tourism marketing campaign and the now-abandoned slogan \"Cooler & Warmer\" kicked off Raimondo's tough month. It ended this week with the heavy Rhode Island presidential primary defeat of Hillary Clinton, for whom Raimondo and most of the state's Democratic establishment had campaigned. In between came the first public poll with Raimondo's job approval ratings, which showed only 31 percent of respondents thought she was doing a good or excellent job. So did Raimondo's message resonate with the 150 or so people who turned out in the Cumberland High School cafeteria? \"Yes and no,\" said Kim Gois, 49, of Cumberland, when asked whether she thought Raimondo was on the right track policy-wise. \"I want a better sense of the direction she is heading.\" Pamela Azar, 58, of Lincoln, said she had come to voice support for charter schools and wanted to find out more about where Raimondo stood on the issue. Even among students there was uncertainty. Cumberland High School senior Christopher Lally, whose business card described him as an entrepreneur and future Babson College student, said he was looking forward to voting for the first time, but couldn't say whether he would vote for Raimondo if she were up for re-election in November. \"What she says tonight will mean a lot,\" Lally said before the event. While the night's tagline was \"upskill Rhode Island,\" the questions from residents largely focused on typical K-12 education issues, such as charter schools, school budgets and high-stakes testing. Some of the discussion touched on issues, such as mandatory recess and changes to the school funding formula, being addressed by the General Assembly as it moves into the heart of legislative season. Asked after the event whether Raimondo had addressed her question about guaranteeing time outdoors during the school day for students, Irena Mandel of Cumberland said the governor had \"sidestepped it.\" Others, such as Jessica Waters, mother of three Cumberland students and Rhode Island Mayoral Academy employee, said she thought Raimondo was listening, even if it was unclear whether she had the policies to solve the state's education challenges. \"This is what we are all about,\" Raimondo said summing up the event with reporters, \"putting forth good proposals and listening to people and getting things done.\"",
