      "title": "Crowds flock to career expo and job fair",
      "text": "Close Cheryl Owens / The Meridian Star \nSylvester Jones, assistant manager with At Home Care, Inc. shows Maricela Albarez what the company provides at the job fair at the Tommy E. Dulaney Center Thursday. featured Crowds flock to career expo and job fair By Cheryl Owens cowens@themeridianstar.com 6 hrs ago Cheryl Owens / The Meridian Star \nSylvester Jones, assistant manager with At Home Care, Inc. shows Maricela Albarez what the company provides at the job fair at the Tommy E. Dulaney Center Thursday. \nHundreds of job seekers flooded the Tommy E. Dulaney Center Thursday in search of a job at the 14th Annual Career Expo and Job Fair hosted by The Radio People and Meridian Community College. \nThis was the third year the fair was conducted at the Tommy E. Dulaney Center and the first year for the Meridian Community College's Health Education and Nursing Division to join the event, said Shannon Coleman, MCC's job placement and career specialist. \n\"We are excited to offer this opportunity to our students and to our community every year,\" said Coleman. \n\"We usually have a separate job fair for our health education and and nursing division, but they joined us this year to do one big job fair. A lot are graduating in May and that's why we chose this time of year to do it, to help them find employment using their degree.\" \nRadio People General Manager Bryan Holladay said the fair gets bigger and better every year. \n\"We had over 45 different companies represented here, and people continued to come into the doors throughout the day,\" Holladay said. \"It was a great opportunity for people to come in and see what jobs are available in Meridian, and also a great opportunity for businesses to meet a lot of different job candidates all at one time.\" \nJob seekers varied from students, to the unemployed, to the employed looking for a better job. \nMaricela Albarez, a nursing student at MCC, said she came to the fair to see what is available in the health care field. \n\"I am working toward getting a higher education, and there are a lot of opportunities out there, so I wanted to see what I might be interested in,\" Alvarez said. \nEddie Roberson, Sr., of Meridian said the job fairs are a meal ticket for him. \n\"I am experienced in doing a lot of things, mostly production type jobs,\" Roberson said. \"It gives me ideas of what I might want to do next, I've worked at Nissan, drove a truck, and can use a forklift, so I am qualified for many things.\" \nRepresentatives from industries such as law enforcement, military, automotive, healthcare, education, fire service, call centers, and direct sale companies were on hand to take applications and screen potential candidates. \nMeridian Police Department Sgt. John Griffith and Meridian Fire Marshall Jason Collier were on hand to provide information about soon to be job openings in their departments. \n\"We will be hiring police officers in about two months,\" Griffith said. \"If you are interested go to Civil Service at City Hall to put in your application.\" \nCollier said the application period is open until May 23 for entry level firefighter. \n\"The next couple of months we will have openings for a diesel mechanic apprentice, and a couple of positions for fire prevention specialists also,\" Collier said. \nNew to the job fair was Firestone Complete Auto Care; Area Manager Rick Herring said the business was excited to be a part of the fair this year. \n\"We were excited about the opportunity to partner up and get some new blood in our stores, and provide employment opportunities to local students who are pursuing a career in technology,\" he said. \nColeman said a workshop was held prior to the fair for those in the community looking for employment. \n\"We discussed with them how to dress for success to make a lasting impression, how to do a good polished resume, and how to interview with confidence,\" Coleman said. \"The more prepared you are, the more successful you will be.\" Sign Up / Sign In With your existing account from... {* loginWidget *}",
