        "title": "Worcester may sue state over mistake in school aid \nMA_Worcester_Telegram WORCESTER – City and school officials are exploring their options – including possibly litigation – to get the state to fix a mistake they said it made in its inflation calculations six years ago, which would net Worcester an extra $12 million in education aid next year.\nAt a joint meeting on Monday, members of the School Committee and City Council agreed to seek the city law office’s advice on whether a statute of limitations would apply in any legal attempt to recoup that money. The School Committee agreed to accept the report of that meeting and the recommendation at its meeting on Thursday night. Councilor-At-Large Morris Bergman, who attended Monday’s meeting, said the request would go before the City Council at its meeting next Tuesday.\nAt the heart of the district’s case is a discrepancy in the state’s inflation factor setting procedure that originated in the latter half of 2010. Brian Allen, the schools’ chief financial and operations officer, said the state should have set the inflation rate at about 6.7 percent at the time.\n“That’s when the economy was going in the tank,” he said. “So the state said, ‘Yikes.’”\nState officials ended up skipping that quarter entirely, and at the end of the year set the inflation factor at around 3 percent, according to Mr. Allen. Since the inflation factor is based on previous inflation rates, that 3.7 percent difference has persisted across the last six years, resulting in incorrectly low rates, Worcester officials say.\nThe city schools would substantially benefit from the corrected higher inflation factor this year, as the district faces a projected $21 million shortfall in its fiscal 2017 budget – a gap that was exacerbated by a rare negative inflation factor this year. The inflation rate is one of two major elements, along with student enrollment, that determine the state’s aid amount to local districts each year, Mr. Allen said. Restoring the skipped 2010 quarter would amount to an extra $12 million in Worcester’s chapter 70 funding, he estimated.\nA month ago, he pleaded Worcester’s case to dozens of lawmakers at the Statehouse. “There was some interest” from the people there in the inflation factor issue, he said, but it amounted to nothing in the House budget, which excluded the inflation factor adjustment, as well as every other change to the state’s school funding formula that was proposed by a legislative task force last year.\n“We’ve been trying to get that mistake changed” for years, said Glenn Koocher, executive director of the Massachusetts Association of School Committees.\nThe current inflation factor is ultimately inaccurate, he added, considering the increase in prices public schools in the state still have to pay for services and goods.\nLike Mr. Allen, he considers the skipped quarter in 2010 a “technical issue” that could be fixed simply by adjusting the current inflation factor to include the excluded percentage from 2010. But it’s been a hard sell to state officials, especially this year, where there isn’t much room in the budget for the roughly $160 million that adjustment would cost the state.\n“Worcester’s the first (city raising the issue) that’s come to my attention,” Mr. Koocher said, who added the city in general “does a much better job at tracking money than most districts do.”\nMr. Bergman, however, said he was “shocked” to learn about the problem for the first time at Monday’s meeting.\n“I put my lawyer’s cap on – there’s usually a six-year statute of limitations in breach of contract situations,” he said, although he added he wasn’t sure exactly what could be done in the specific case of the state's inflation factor.\n“Moe raised the question – can we at least ask the law department (for the city)?” said School Committee member Jack Foley, who also was at Monday’s meeting.\nMr. Foley added he could see Worcester trying to bring other towns and cities adversely affected by the inflation factor into its effort to raise the issue with the state – “we’d certainly have better standing,” he said.\nWhile he didn’t have much hope in a legal action being effective, Mr. Koocher also believes Worcester’s attempt to highlight the problem can only help.\n“Anything you can throw out in the public discourse during budget season raises awareness,” he said, adding he is still hopeful the state Senate, which has yet to release its recommended budget for next year, will incorporate the inflation factor fix, as well as other funding formula changes, into its spending plan.\nScott O’Connell can be reached at Scott.O’Connell@telegram.com. Follow him on Twitter @ScottOConnellTG",
